=========================================
C++ LAMBDA FUNCTIONS (C++11)
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is a Lambda Function?
-----------------------------
A lambda function is an anonymous (unnamed) function in C++.

It is mainly used for:
- short inline logic
- callbacks
- STL algorithms (for_each, sort, find_if)

Key points:
✔ No name
✔ Can take parameters
✔ Can return values
✔ Defined inline

-----------------------------------------

2. Basic Syntax
---------------

[capture](parameters) -> return_type {
    // body
};

Example:
auto f = []() {
    cout << "Hello World";
};

f();

-----------------------------------------

3. Lambda Execution
-------------------

Define + call immediately:

[]() {
    cout << "Hello World";
}();

-----------------------------------------

4. Lambda with Return Value
---------------------------

auto result = []() -> int {
    return 100;
}();

cout << result;

-----------------------------------------

5. Using std::function
----------------------

Used when we want to store lambda in a variable with explicit type.

#include <functional>

std::function<int(int,int)> add =
[](int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
};

cout << add(2, 3);

-----------------------------------------

6. Using Lambda with STL (IMPORTANT)
------------------------------------

#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>

vector<int> v = {1,2,3,4,5};

for_each(v.begin(), v.end(),
[](int x) {
    cout << x << " ";
});

-----------------------------------------

7. Capture Clause (MOST IMPORTANT)
----------------------------------

Used to access outer variables inside lambda.

-----------------------------------------

✔ [=] → Capture all by VALUE
✔ [&] → Capture all by REFERENCE

Example:

int var = 10;

auto f = [=]() {
    // var is copied (cannot modify original)
};

auto g = [&]() {
    // var is reference (can modify original)
};

-----------------------------------------

8. Selective Capture
--------------------

int var = 10;
int var2 = 20;

auto f = [var, &var2]() {
    // var  → value (read-only copy)
    // var2 → reference (can modify)
};

-----------------------------------------

9. Example (Modify Outer Variable)
----------------------------------

vector<int> v = {1,2,3,4};

int sum = 0;

for_each(v.begin(), v.end(),
[&](int x) {
    sum += x;
});

cout << sum;

-----------------------------------------

10. Why use Lambda?
-------------------

✔ Reduces boilerplate code
✔ Useful for STL algorithms
✔ No need to define separate function
✔ Improves readability for small logic

-----------------------------------------

11. Interview One-liner
-----------------------

A lambda is an anonymous inline function introduced in C++11
used for short operations and STL algorithms, with support for
capture of external variables by value or reference.

